obo:ECO_0005589  a  owl:Class .

gomodel:SYNGO_671  a      owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: The SV protein CSPalpha is not essential for synaptic transmission, but acts as a chaperone for SNAP-25 to regulate the synaptic vesicle cycle (i.e. SV recycling and SV priming).\n\nCSPalpha KO NMJ nerve terminals were analyzed by electrophysiology (Fig. 1) and they exhibit a reduction in the RRP due to a defect in vesicle priming (Fig. 1H) - probably due to a loss of SNAP-25 (Fig. 2). Measurements of Synapto-pHluorin (SpH) fluorescence in response to high-frequency trains of action potentials reveals an impairment of vesicle recycling/endocytosis in CSPalpha KO terminals (Fig.4-6).. Experimental description: Littermate offspring obtained from matings of the CSP-α-KO-spHtg line was used for experiments." ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0001-7351-8706" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-0755-5899" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-3185-5709" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-0938-8534" ;
        dc:date           "2017-08-16" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_671" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

